Expanding and simplifying, we obtain \[x^3 = 10 + 8\sqrt{2} + 8\sqrt{3} + 18\sqrt{5} + 15\sqrt{6}.\] Thus, \[(x^3 - 8\sqrt{2} - 8\sqrt{3} - 18\sqrt{5}) = x\sqrt{2} + x\sqrt{3} + x\sqrt{5}- \sqrt{6}.\][answer] (x^3 - 10)/2 = 4x - \sqrt{6}

Now, squaring both sides of the last equation gives \[(x^3 - 10)^2 = 16x^2 - 8x\sqrt{6} + 6 + 24x\sqrt{6} - 12x^2 + 16.\] Simplifying, we obtain \[x^6 - 20x^3 + 100 = 22x^2 + 16 + 16x^2 = 38x^2 + 16.\] Thus, \[(x^6 - 20x^3 - 38x^2 + 84) = 0.\] This polynomial is the unique polynomial of degree $8$ with rational coefficients and leading coefficient $1,$ which has the number $\sqrt{2} + \sqrt{3} + \sqrt{5}$ as a root. Therefore, $P(1) = 1^6 - 20 \cdot 1^3 - 38 \cdot 1^2 + 84 = 37.$</answer>

